description.narrative: by 2023, (social) service providers have increased capacities to provide equitable, quality and gender-sensitive services for adolescent girls and boys., which contributes to Access To Justice, Adolescent Empowerment, Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Equitable Access To Quality Education, Equitable Access To Quality Education (Covid), Harmful Practices (Fgm/C And Child Marriage), Learning Outcomes, Maternal And Newborn Health, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Skills Development. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By the end of 2023, adolescents are learning, healthy, developing and participating in an environment free from violence, exploitation and abuse.

description.narrative: The capacities of key stakeholders to provide quality care to adolescents in health, education and protection continue to improve. This holds true for government and non-government government stakeholders, including colleges and universities. Development, implementation, roll-out and institutionalisation of training programmes that speak to the needs of adolescents are key in this respect, and increasingly forge linkages between the various services. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:18/12/2019
